	<div class="row">
		<div class="small-12 columns">
			<h3>
				Scientific Motivation
			</h3>
            <p>
            The increasing spatial and temporal resolution of spectro-polarimeter observations, statistical studies based on unprecedentedly huge samples of stars obtained from space-borne observatories like KEPLER and COROT, and the use of massively parallel supercomputers have rapidly changed our view of stellar magnetic activity and variability throughout stellar evolution. This wealth of observational information is progressively getting closer to the richness of solar observations, for which continuous monitoring is now available at extremely high spatial resolution and throughout the electromagnetic spectrum (HINODE, SDO).
            </p>
            <p>
            Solar like stars are on the lower main sequence and are known to show chromospheric activity similar to that on the Sun in the Ca II H and K emission. Magnetic activity shows erratic, multi or single periodic behavior, interrupted by long quiescent periods of activity (grand minima). What is the origin of this broad range of variability in stellar activity?
            </p>
            <p>
            In solar like stars, the cyclic activity is ascribed to a dynamo mechanism maintained through differential rotation at the tachocline. However the tachocline moves towards increasing depths with later spectral types, disappearing around M4. Thus, a direct comparison between the stellar activity in solar-type with lower-mass stars is essential for the understanding of the effect of stellar mass on the resulting magnetic activity through a dynamo mechanism.
            </p>
            <p>
            This Splinter is aimed at offering a synthetic view of the recent progresses in the domain of variability of stellar magnetism and activity from different perspectives. We invite terrestrial, solar and stellar astrophysicists to present their latest results, as there is an intimate interplay between magnetic activity and variability of our Sun and cool stars.
            </p>
            
